                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1065">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5034 (China) Thrift Corp./60: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-11-21T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 21, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 21—3:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>101. Peiping’s November 18, 4 p.m.<note n="12" xml:id="d1065fn12">Not
                        printed.</note> Suma<note n="13" xml:id="d1065fn13">Yakichiro Suma, First
                        Secretary of the Japanese Embassy in China at Nanking.</note> has informed
                    me today that the Japanese Consul General in Harbin will take measures to
                    prevent the publication in Japanese papers of the attacks connected with the
                    Thriftcor Bank brought to his attention by the American Ambassador.</p>
                <p>By mail to Shanghai, for the Ambassador. Repeated to Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
